07330FD4A18546278C2465DC1BC786E7.description:
Energy cannot be created or destroyed—only moves between one place and another place,
between objects and/or fields, or between systems.

C53F4E78D0FB4C16A3AC3894A6EC756B.description: The total amount of energy and matter in closed systems is conserved.

FE270CF86D28446FA583E3F9F1E7B6B2.description:
Models can be used to predict the behavior of a system, but these predictions have limited
precision and reliability due to the assumptions and approximations inherent in models.

D82D0C4A2A38447FB2D4A655ED1A08E5.description:
Models (e.g., physical, mathematical, computer models) can be used to simulate systems and
interactions—including energy, matter, and information flows—within and between systems at
different scales.

1E8D60A13AF2415A982B76336C333C6C.description:
When investigating or describing a system, the boundaries and initial conditions of the system
need to be defined and their inputs and outputs analyzed and described using models.

E4860E404A5B424A9C65340C2C054B10.description: Systems can be designed to do specific tasks.

F585F25182114B389F56424D87BF5DE9.description:
A system is an organized group of related objects or components; models can be used for
understanding and predicting the behavior of systems.

CD675323D4A8466BB472116B5A1DE128.description: Changes in systems may have various causes that may not have equal effects.

04015AC86A324A12B9500D955E2AB8D3.description: Systems can be designed to cause a desired effect.

3C71EF7B771C4B9BB575798F5E2C9C7F.description:
Patterns of performance of designed systems can be analyzed and interpreted to reengineer and
improve the system.

B99CD065008B4A1DB2789ACEC3186963.description:
Criteria may need to be broken down into simpler ones that can be approached systematically,
and decisions about the priority of certain criteria over others (tradeoffs) may be needed. (secondary
to HS-PS1-6)

7ED60FA7B1E4421B9EF2CC18CA08BEA3.description:
When evaluating solutions, it is important to take into account a range of constraints, including
cost, safety, reliability, and aesthetics, and to consider social, cultural, and environmental impacts.
(HS-ETS1-3)

4BC526579FC9457086D4FC4B6E76AB32.description:
Information can be digitized (e.g., a picture stored as the values of an array of pixels); in this form,
it can be stored reliably in computer memory and sent over long distances as a series of wave
pulses. (HS-PS4-2), (HSPS4-5)

76197E30AFB142F2A96B530C4DC82AAB.description: The availability of energy limits what can occur in any system. (HS-PS3-1)

636CD8806FC84A2DAD316702310EA1F9.description:
Mathematical expressions, which quantify how the stored energy in a system depends on its
configuration (e.g. relative positions of charged particles, compression of a spring) and how kinetic
energy depends on mass and speed, allow the concept of conservation of energy to be used to
predict and describe system behavior.

192E28358C404E8E8376209571387B70.description:
Energy cannot be created or destroyed, but it can be transported from one place to another and
transferred between systems. (HS-PS3-1), (HS-PS3-4)

33CF73CC665544AF950081B401CA9DD0.description:
Conservation of energy means that the total change of energy in any system is always equal to the
total energy transferred into or out of the system. (HS-PS3-1)

7F89A77F64364F9D8241C72A762E5F75.description:
At the macroscopic scale, energy manifests itself in multiple ways, such as in motion, sound, light,
and thermal energy . (HSPS3-2), (HS-PS3-3)

2D12BE20A42D47988D5244D932175639.description:
Energy is a quantitative property of a system that depends on the motion and interactions of matter
and radiation within that system. That there is a single quantity called energy is due to the fact that a
system’s total energy is conserved, even as, within the system, energy is continually transferred
from one object to another and between its various possible forms.

1CEFC868BC794B2E9AFBA283B9374E0B.description:

principles, empirical evidence, and/or logical arguments regarding relevant factors (e.g. economic,
societal, environmental, ethical considerations).

A9EBCF96D1B342D3977EADF66B88B06C.description:
(+) Use inverse functions to solve trigonometric equations that arise in modeling contexts; evaluate
the solutions using technology, and interpret them in terms of the context.

8AC612DCF2CF428E868A3E881DEF4C46.description: Interpret the parameters in a linear or exponential function in terms of a context.

CB4267BA909646DF9CEB609D0288BE94.description:
Understand that the graph of an equation in two variables is the set of all its solutions plotted in the
coordinate plane, often forming a curve (which could be a line).

AFC0B1F70F674D93AF2E6230ACAB4A80.description:
Solve linear equations and inequalities in one variable, including equations with coefficients
represented by letters.

53AE27629E5144AEB7D67ED0C9F09620.description:
Explain each step in solving a simple equation as following from the equality of numbers asserted at
the previous step, starting from the assumption that the original equation has a solution. Construct a
viable argument to justify a solution method.

B7967A8B8FBC4EFE8C1FA53106BD1FB9.description:
Rearrange formulas to highlight a quantity of interest, using the same reasoning as in solving
equations. For example, rearrange Ohm’s law V = IR to highlight resistance R.

82F831CA4C9F43B6B7D0BEC493B366DE.description: Interpret parts of an expression, such as terms, factors, and coefficients.

5FC3ACCB23A6438CA7E130F33BACB652.description:
Given two vectors in magnitude and direction form, determine the magnitude and direction of their
sum.

E2FC3E63F1EF4F6093457401AA833308.description: Choose a level of accuracy appropriate to limitations on measurement when reporting quantities.

1702A32CE4FE489AAF49A0E7992E3405.description:
Use units as a way to understand problems and to guide the solution of multistep problems; choose
and interpret units consistently in formulas; choose and interpret the scale and the origin in graphs
and data displays.

F4D145B8E50647FD959BAA81FF7DDFC0.description:
Acquire and use accurately a range of general academic and domain-specific words and phrases
sufficient for reading, writing, speaking, and listening at the college and career readiness level;
demonstrate independence in gathering vocabulary knowledge when encountering an unknown term
important to comprehension or expression.

C9E49C91C0EB432A97641BBB39BA6F73.description: Demonstrate understanding of word relationships and nuances in word meanings.

E2183FEB5D3B4AAB95A1EAD4C4E86177.description:
Determine or clarify the meaning of unknown and multiple-meaning words and phrases by using
context clues, analyzing meaningful word parts, and consulting general and specialized reference
materials, as appropriate.

6A5EE39FD0474D7FBFA87024AEADA671.description:
Apply knowledge of language to understand how language functions in different contexts, to make
effective choices for meaning or style, and to comprehend more fully when reading or listening.

FBCE2BE9AB914853B9AF4052ACFD7148.description:
Demonstrate command of the conventions of standard English capitalization, punctuation, and
spelling when writing.

71AAB01FF0C1427EACE23D7562511783.description:
Demonstrate command of the conventions of standard English grammar and usage when writing or
speaking.

FBCDD72D8BAC43049412029F662A15B0.description:
Adapt speech to a variety of contexts and communicative tasks, demonstrating command of formal
English when indicated or appropriate.

4A124E5571204409BBB331B7F385B1A1.description:
Make strategic use of digital media and visual displays of data to express information and enhance
understanding of presentations.

5352605B51C74C77AD346D8902D052B6.description:
Present information, findings, and supporting evidence such that listeners can follow the line of
reasoning and the organization, development, and style are appropriate to task, purpose, and
audience.

AA5629E133594E8BA5289168681E8435.description:
Integrate and evaluate information presented in diverse media and formats, including visually,
quantitatively, and orally.

9F2080250D5D41579402D2AD68E164AA.description:
Prepare for and participate effectively in a range of conversations and collaborations with diverse
partners, building on others’ ideas and expressing their own clearly and persuasively.

7CBEDE9573A34D389923D5CC23AB53C8.description: Draw evidence from literary or informational texts to support analysis, reflection, and research.

A551DA5017F44B6F975F2C0366CA590B.description:
Gather relevant information from multiple print and digital sources, assess the credibility and
accuracy of each source, and integrate the information while avoiding plagiarism.

7A6AD46FF17249C49EE4A07D3914D96B.description:
Produce clear and coherent writing in which the development, organization, and style are
appropriate to task, purpose, and audience.

EE449730E0954FB2BA197136958E9406.description: Write narratives to develop real or imagined experiences or events using effective technique, wellchosen details, and well-structured event sequences.

28EC3130B9A6488794211104F67FC56E.description:
Write informative/explanatory texts to examine and convey complex ideas and information clearly
and accurately through the effective selection, organization, and analysis of content.

40E1B2E2EE654CF0A2C94AB4B43CC85E.description: Read and comprehend complex literary and informational texts independently and proficiently.

39107FED54E8438C807162BC9C7727EC.description:
Integrate and evaluate content presented in diverse formats and media, including visually and
quantitatively, as well as in words.

4DAE50D6D09D41368E498CDBC65BA0CA.description:
Determine central ideas or themes of a text and analyze their development; summarize the key
supporting details and ideas.

1FCE3552D36B4EA6A4AE988D0CB0BFCD.description:
Read closely to determine what the text says explicitly and to make logical inferences from it; cite
specific textual evidence when writing or speaking to support conclusions drawn from the text.
